        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Incident Volume and Trend Analysis"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Raw MTTx metrics tell you how fast you respond to incidents. Incident volume and trend analysis tells you whether you are having more or fewer incidents over time \u2014 and why. This is the leading indicator of reliability trajectory: a team that resolves incidents quickly but has rising volume is running harder to stay in place."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What to Measure"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Track incident volume across three dimensions simultaneously. Looking at any single dimension in isolation produces misleading conclusions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Volume by Severity Over Time"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Plot monthly incident counts broken down by severity (SEV-1, SEV-2, SEV-3) over a rolling 12-month window. This reveals:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Whether total volume is rising, falling, or stable"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Whether the severity distribution is shifting (more SEV-1s relative to SEV-3s is a signal of worsening blast radius or slower detection)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Seasonal patterns tied to traffic growth, model releases, or team capacity (e.g., incidents spike in January when traffic resumes after holiday dips)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Volume by Root Cause Category"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tag every incident with a structured root cause label (see the previous sub-subtopic) and aggregate counts by category over rolling 90 days. This answers: where is your incident volume coming from? A team that knows 34% of incidents are model-quality issues knows exactly where to invest in monitoring and prevention."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Recurrence Rate"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Track the fraction of incidents that share a root cause with a prior incident in the same 90-day window. This is the single most important leading indicator of systemic reliability health. Volume can be stable or even falling, but if recurrence rate is high, the team is solving symptoms rather than causes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Incident Volume Trend Analysis Dashboard"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Building the Trend Analysis Pipeline"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Trend analysis requires structured, queryable incident data. The most common failure is storing incident information in narrative formats (Confluence pages, Slack threads, email) that cannot be queried programmatically."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Minimum Viable Incident Data Schema"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Minimum fields required for trend analysis\nINCIDENT_SCHEMA = {\n    \"id\": str,                    # unique incident identifier\n    \"created_at\": \"datetime\",     # when the incident was opened\n    \"severity\": str,              # SEV-1, SEV-2, SEV-3\n    \"title\": str,                 # short description\n    \"root_cause_labels\": list,    # [\"model:drift\", \"capacity:gpu-exhaustion\"]\n    \"timestamps\": {\n        \"failure_onset\": \"datetime\",     # when failure actually started\n        \"detected_at\": \"datetime\",\n        \"acknowledged_at\": \"datetime\",\n        \"mitigated_at\": \"datetime\",\n        \"resolved_at\": \"datetime\",\n    },\n    \"affected_services\": list,    # [\"inference-api\", \"embedding-service\"]\n    \"postmortem_url\": str,        # link to postmortem if one was written\n    \"action_item_ids\": list,      # links to created action items\n}\n\n# Derived fields computed at query time\n# mttd_minutes = (detected_at - failure_onset).total_seconds() / 60\n# mttr_minutes  = (mitigated_at - failure_onset).total_seconds() / 60"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Computing the Core Trend Metrics"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import pandas as pd\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta\n\ndef incident_volume_report(incidents: list[dict], window_days: int = 90) -> dict:\n    df = pd.DataFrame(incidents)\n    df[\"created_at\"] = pd.to_datetime(df[\"created_at\"])\n    df[\"month\"] = df[\"created_at\"].dt.to_period(\"M\")\n\n    cutoff = datetime.utcnow() - timedelta(days=window_days)\n    recent = df[df[\"created_at\"] >= cutoff]\n\n    # Volume by severity x month\n    volume_trend = (\n        df.groupby([\"month\", \"severity\"])\n        .size()\n        .unstack(fill_value=0)\n        .sort_index()\n    )\n\n    # Root cause distribution (recent window)\n    cause_labels = recent.explode(\"root_cause_labels\")[\"root_cause_labels\"]\n    cause_dist = cause_labels.value_counts(normalize=True)\n\n    # Recurrence rate\n    seen = set()\n    recurring = 0\n    for _, row in recent.iterrows():\n        labels = set(row[\"root_cause_labels\"])\n        if labels & seen:\n            recurring += 1\n        seen |= labels\n    recurrence_rate = recurring / len(recent) if len(recent) > 0 else 0\n\n    # SEV-1 fraction trend (rolling 3-month vs prior 3-month)\n    three_months_ago = datetime.utcnow() - timedelta(days=90)\n    six_months_ago = datetime.utcnow() - timedelta(days=180)\n    recent_sev1_frac = (\n        len(df[(df[\"created_at\"] >= three_months_ago) & (df[\"severity\"] == \"SEV-1\")])\n        / max(1, len(df[df[\"created_at\"] >= three_months_ago]))\n    )\n\n    return {\n        \"volume_trend\": volume_trend.to_dict(),\n        \"cause_distribution\": cause_dist.to_dict(),\n        \"recurrence_rate\": recurrence_rate,\n        \"sev1_fraction_90d\": recent_sev1_frac,\n        \"total_incidents_90d\": len(recent),\n    }"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Interpreting Trend Signals"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Different volume patterns require different responses. The goal is not to minimise incident count at all costs \u2014 that produces under-reporting \u2014 but to understand what the trend means and respond to the signal."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Declining Total Volume"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The desired outcome. Indicates that systemic fixes are working, monitoring improvements are catching issues before they escalate, or deployment practices have improved."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Watch for a false positive: volume declining because the team has stopped filing SEV-3 incidents (under-reporting), not because fewer things are going wrong. Cross-check with SLO data and user-reported error rates."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stable High Volume"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stable volume sounds acceptable but is not, if the volume is above the team's sustainable pace. Stable high volume typically means:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
