        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Increasing SEV-1 Fraction"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Total volume may be stable, but if SEV-1 incidents are growing as a percentage, reliability is actually worsening in the dimension that matters most to customers. Two causes are common:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Blast radius is growing "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "\u2014 failures that previously affected a small fraction of traffic now affect more, due to increased dependency coupling or reduced redundancy",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "italic"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Detection is slow "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "\u2014 SEV-3 incidents are not being detected early, so they escalate to SEV-1 before the on-call team can intervene. This is a MTTD problem, not a fundamental reliability problem",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "italic"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Distinguish between these two by checking whether MTTD has increased for the incidents that escalated to SEV-1. If MTTD is growing, invest in alerting. If MTTD is stable, the blast radius is genuinely larger."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Normalisation for Fair Comparison"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Raw incident counts are misleading when request volume, team size, or service scope changes over time. Normalise before drawing conclusions:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Incidents per Million Requests"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def incidents_per_million_requests(incidents, request_counts_by_month):\n    \"\"\"\n    Normalise incident volume by traffic to detect whether incidents\n    are growing faster or slower than traffic.\n    \"\"\"\n    df = pd.DataFrame(incidents)\n    df[\"month\"] = pd.to_datetime(df[\"created_at\"]).dt.to_period(\"M\")\n\n    monthly_counts = df.groupby(\"month\").size().rename(\"incidents\")\n    monthly_requests = pd.Series(request_counts_by_month, name=\"requests\")\n\n    joined = pd.concat([monthly_counts, monthly_requests], axis=1).dropna()\n    joined[\"incidents_per_million\"] = (\n        joined[\"incidents\"] / joined[\"requests\"] * 1_000_000\n    )\n    return joined"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "If incidents per million requests is declining while raw incident count is stable, your reliability is actually improving \u2014 the system is handling more traffic with the same absolute failure count. If incidents per million is rising, reliability is degrading even if raw count looks flat."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "New Service Scope"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a new service is added to the platform, total incident volume will naturally increase. Segment incidents by service or component to avoid conflating growth with regression. Track:"
          }
        ]
